                    '5' => 'Expert decision-making: conducts a rapid but thorough risk-benefit analysis considering all factors. Recognises the unique downstream challenge: at 19 km/h over ground, the vessel cannot simply stop — the current will continue to carry it. Evaluating options: (1) emergency anchor in the Wachau narrows — high risk of swinging into the channel or bank in current, could obstruct the waterway and create danger for the cruise ship ahead if it reverses; (2) finding an ad-hoc bank mooring — extremely hazardous at night in unfamiliar section without detailed charts; (3) continuing to the next designated mooring at reduced speed using multi-sensor navigation — manageable risk if systematic approach is maintained. Chooses option 3 with explicit abort criteria and communicates the full plan to viadonau traffic service. Requests traffic service to provide real-time navigational guidance through the critical sections if available. Asks RIS to alert any upstream traffic of the vessel\'s degraded navigation status. Monitors the situation continuously and is prepared to anchor if the abort criteria are met (inability to positively identify the channel ahead). After reaching the safe mooring, will not depart until the primary ECDIS is repaired or detailed up-to-date charts are obtained for the remaining route. Files a navigation equipment failure report.',
