        'briefing_json' => [
            'en' => [
                'situation'           => 'You are Master of a 110m x 11.4m inland tanker carrying 2,200 tonnes of heating oil on the Rhine near Duisburg, Europe\'s largest inland port, in an area of dense commercial traffic. Your vessel is drawing 3.2m. While transiting near Rhine kilometre 780, the vessel strikes a submerged object with a heavy impact felt throughout the hull. The object is later identified as a lost shipping container from a container barge that reported a deck cargo loss approximately two hours earlier — a VHF warning was broadcast but your vessel was in a lock at the time and you did not receive the message. The impact has damaged the hull forward on the starboard side. The forepeak tank has been breached and is taking water rapidly. The collision bulkhead appears to be holding but upon inspection there is visible inward deformation of the plating, with cracking around two rivet lines. Your forward draft is increasing — from the loaded draft of 3.2m to 3.5m within the first ten minutes of flooding, suggesting progressive and potentially accelerating flooding of the forepeak space. The channel depth at your current position is 4.2m — with your increasing forward draft approaching 3.5m and rising, your under-keel clearance is diminishing to dangerously low levels and you risk grounding in the channel if the flooding continues. The cargo tanks themselves are currently intact, but the hull deformation extends close to the forward boundary of the No. 1 cargo tank — there is concern that structural failure could propagate into the cargo space. If cargo tanks are breached, 2,200 tonnes of heating oil entering the Rhine would cause an environmental catastrophe affecting drinking water intakes, ecosystems, and downstream communities for hundreds of kilometres. Dense traffic surrounds you: a fully loaded push convoy (a push boat with four barges, approximately 185m combined length) is 800m astern heading in the same direction, and a passenger vessel is approaching from ahead at a range of approximately 1,200m. You must make critical decisions quickly: do you attempt to reach the nearest port facility at Duisburg, approximately 3 km ahead, or do you intentionally ground the vessel on the shallow bank to prevent sinking in the fairway? The Wasserschutzpolizei (waterway police) must be notified immediately, and surrounding traffic must be warned that you are becoming an obstruction and a potential pollution source.',
