                    '1' => 'No systematic damage assessment. Does not monitor the flooding rate or draft increase. Makes no decision on whether to continue or ground — drifts without action. Does not assess the integrity of the collision bulkhead or the proximity of damage to the cargo tanks.',
                    '2' => 'Sends someone to look at the damage but does not act on the information. Aware the forepeak is flooding but does not track the rate. Does not correlate the increasing draft with the available channel depth. Makes a panic decision without proper assessment — either rushes for port or grounds immediately without weighing the options.',
                    '3' => 'Conducts a basic damage assessment: determines the forepeak is breached and flooding, monitors the forward draft increase, notes the collision bulkhead deformation. Starts the bilge pump in the forepeak. Makes a reasoned decision on continue vs. ground based on the flooding rate and distance to port. Deploys crew to monitor the bulkhead and No. 1 cargo tank boundary.',
                    '4' => 'Systematic damage assessment and response: immediately orders continuous monitoring of forward draft (reading every 2 minutes), deploys the portable salvage pump to supplement bilge pumps, assigns the engineer to assess the collision bulkhead integrity from inside the forepeak access. Calculates the flooding rate: 0.3m draft increase in 10 minutes suggests approximately 30-40 tonnes of water — extrapolates to estimate when the draft will reach the channel depth limit (4.2m). With 3 km to Duisburg at approximately 10 km/h (allowing for reduced speed), transit time is about 18 minutes. If the flooding rate remains constant, the draft will reach approximately 3.9-4.0m by the time the vessel reaches Duisburg — tight but potentially feasible if the flooding does not accelerate. Decides to proceed to Duisburg at reduced speed while monitoring closely, with a clear abort point: if the draft reaches 3.8m before passing the halfway point, immediately grounds on the bank. Prepares the crew for both outcomes. Assesses the structural crack propagation risk — if the collision bulkhead is weakening, the decision shifts immediately to controlled grounding.',
                    '5' => 'Expert damage management: establishes a structured assessment protocol immediately. Forward draft readings every 2 minutes logged and plotted to determine flooding rate trend (constant, increasing, or stabilising). Engineer inspects the collision bulkhead using all accessible viewpoints and reports on: plate deformation depth, crack lengths and propagation direction, any weeping or water ingress through the bulkhead, proximity of deformation to the No. 1 cargo tank boundary. Starts both bilge pumps and the portable salvage pump — monitors pump output versus water ingress to determine if flooding can be slowed. Performs a critical calculation: at current flooding rate, what is the time to reach 4.0m draft (maximum safe draft for 4.2m channel) — this gives the "decision window." Compares this against transit time to Duisburg at reduced speed. If the flooding rate is stable and the vessel can reach Duisburg before 4.0m draft with margin: proceeds to port where proper response equipment (pollution booms, cranes, repair capacity) is available. If the flooding rate is accelerating or the bulkhead shows signs of failure: immediately initiates controlled grounding on a pre-selected bank section (identifies soft-bottom areas from the chart to minimise hull damage, avoids areas near drinking water intakes). Before grounding: starts transferring heating oil internally from No. 1 tank to aft tanks to reduce the forward structural load and move cargo away from the damage zone. Pre-positions oil spill containment booms at deck level ready for deployment. All calculations and decisions documented with timestamps.',
