                    '4' => 'Proactive pollution prevention: treats the cargo tank integrity as the highest priority in the crisis. Assigns crew to continuously monitor No. 1 tank — checking for oil leakage into the damaged forepeak (which would indicate a tank breach), monitoring tank ullages for any unexplained level changes. Considers transferring cargo from No. 1 tank to aft tanks to reduce the load on the damaged forward structure and move the oil away from the vulnerability zone. Prepares all onboard spill containment equipment for immediate deployment. Notifies the Wasserschutzpolizei with explicit pollution risk information: cargo type, quantity, tank status, estimated risk level. Requests the port authority to pre-position pollution response equipment (booms, skimmers) at the approach to Duisburg. Identifies downstream drinking water intakes on the chart and recognises the downstream impact if a spill occurs.',
                    '5' => 'Expert pollution prevention and environmental protection: establishes pollution prevention as the strategic priority that drives all other decisions. Implements a multi-layer approach: (1) Structural protection: orders immediate start of cargo transfer from No. 1 tank to aft tanks using the vessel\'s cargo pumps — this reduces hydrostatic pressure on the damaged forward structure and moves oil away from the damage zone. (2) Monitoring: continuous tank integrity monitoring — ullages, visual inspection of tank top and boundaries, sounding of the forepeak for oil contamination (which would indicate tank breach). (3) Containment preparation: all onboard booms and absorbent materials readied for deployment, deck scuppers plugged to prevent any deck oil from reaching the water. (4) Authority notification: structured pollution risk report to Wasserschutzpolizei including: cargo manifest (2,200 tonnes heating oil), current tank status (intact but at risk), structural assessment, vessel intentions, request for shore-based pollution response. (5) Pre-positioning: requests Duisburg port to deploy containment booms across the harbour approach as a precautionary measure. (6) Downstream notification: alerts the waterway authority to notify downstream drinking water treatment plants to increase monitoring and prepare to close intakes if necessary. Recognises that the decision to ground vs. proceed to port must account for pollution response capability: Duisburg has professional response equipment while a random bank location does not. This factor influences the continue-or-ground decision. Documents all pollution prevention actions for regulatory and insurance purposes.',
