                    '3' => 'Performs the basic draft calculation: Kaub gauge 78 cm gives approximately 1.9m channel depth, minus 20 cm minimum UKC, gives 1.7m maximum draft. References hydrostatic tables to determine that 1.7m draft corresponds to approximately 1,200 tonnes. Loads accordingly. Understands that exceeding this limit risks grounding at Kaub.',
                    '4' => 'Thorough draft management: performs the Kaub calculation correctly (1.9m depth, 1.7m max draft, ~1,200 tonnes) and extends the analysis to other critical points on the Rhine — checks Oestrich gauge, Maxau gauge, and other controlling depths for the Basel-bound transit. Accounts for the vessel\'s trim (steel coils loaded aft could create a stern-heavy trim, increasing the stern draft beyond the mean). Considers the effect of squat at transit speed in shallow water — at reduced UKC, hydrodynamic squat further reduces the effective clearance. Applies a conservative safety margin beyond the regulatory minimum. Checks that the Kaub traffic light system\'s published maximum draft is not lower than the calculated maximum. Verifies gauges on the morning of departure, not just the day before, since levels can change overnight.',
                    '5' => 'Expert draft and loading management: conducts a comprehensive analysis covering every aspect of safe draft determination. Kaub calculation with full rigour: gauge reading 78 cm → chart datum + gauge conversion → actual water depth 1.9m → subtract regulatory minimum UKC (20 cm) → maximum static draft 1.7m → further subtract squat allowance at planned transit speed (estimated 10-15 cm in the Kaub narrows at 10 km/h through water, using the vessel\'s known squat characteristics) → operational maximum draft approximately 1.55-1.60m → consult hydrostatic tables for this draft → approximately 1,000-1,100 tonnes rather than 1,200. Extends the analysis to all controlling gauges along the route. Considers dynamic factors: (a) water level may continue falling during the 3-4 day transit to Basel — checks the trend, and if falling, reduces the load further or plans to pass Kaub quickly before levels drop more; (b) swell from passing traffic in the narrows creates momentary depth reduction; (c) steel coils must be loaded to achieve even keel or very slight stern trim — calculates the loading plan to ensure the critical draft is amidships where the channel depth is measured. Builds in explicit margin and refuses to load to the absolute theoretical maximum. Documents the loading calculation and keeps it aboard for inspection by the WSA traffic light control at Kaub. Plans to declare the actual draft honestly to the Kaub system — no underreporting.',
