                    '1' => 'No commercial analysis. Either accepts the first option without evaluation or refuses the cargo entirely. No consideration of the financial implications of each option. Does not account for the enhanced freight rate or the competitive situation.',
                    '2' => 'Chooses an option but without financial reasoning. Does not calculate the revenue, costs, or net result of each alternative. Does not consider the competitive pressure or the opportunity cost of waiting. Makes a decision based on gut feeling rather than analysis.',
                    '3' => 'Evaluates the three options with basic financial reasoning. Calculates approximate revenue for each scenario (considering the 180% surcharge rate). Recognises the competitive pressure — if the cargo is lost to another operator, the vessel earns nothing. Chooses the option that appears to maximise revenue while staying within safe operational limits. Communicates the decision to the shipper with a rationale.',
                    '4' => 'Detailed commercial analysis: constructs a financial comparison of all three options. Option (a) double trip: revenue from 2,800 tonnes at 180% rate minus the additional €85,000 cost and 14 days of vessel time (14 x €3,500 = €49,000 in fixed costs for the second trip). Option (b) partial load + rail: revenue from 1,200 tonnes at 180% rate minus the €30,000 concession, vessel completes in ~7 days and is available for the next cargo. Option (c) wait: €3,500/day idle cost for 5-7 days (€17,500-€24,500) with uncertain outcome — if water rises, can load 2,200 tonnes but may lose the cargo to competitors while waiting. Also considers a fourth option: negotiate with the shipper for a partial load at the full rate (no €30,000 discount) given the market conditions — in a low-water market, vessel capacity is scarce and the shipper may accept. Selects the option with the best risk-adjusted return. Considers vessel availability for subsequent cargoes — a quick turnaround enables earning on multiple low-water surcharge cargoes.',
                    '5' => 'Expert commercial optimisation in a low-water market: treats this as a strategic decision, not just a single cargo choice. Builds a comprehensive financial model: (1) Option (a): calculates total revenue (2,800 tonnes x rate), total cost (€85,000 additional + 14 days x €3,500 fixed), net result, and daily earning rate (total profit / total days). (2) Option (b): calculates net revenue (1,200 tonnes x rate - €30,000 concession), trip duration ~7 days, daily earning rate, plus the value of having the vessel free for the next cargo in the ongoing low-water period (where every available vessel is earning premium rates). (3) Option (c): calculates the expected value accounting for probability of water rising (assigns probability based on forecast reliability — perhaps 60% chance of Kaub 150 in 7 days), the daily idle cost, and the risk of losing the cargo while waiting. (4) Proposes a creative fourth option: negotiate a split shipment where 1,200 tonnes go by vessel at full rate (no discount — the market supports it), remaining 1,600 tonnes by rail at the shipper\'s expense, and the vessel is free in 7 days to take another premium-rate cargo. Argues that in a sustained low-water market, vessel utilisation rate matters more than maximising tonnes per trip — a quick turnaround at 180% rates generates more revenue over a month than a double trip. Analyses competitor behaviour: three other vessels negotiating means the cargo will move regardless — the question is whether you get the profitable 1,200-tonne portion. Also considers: insurance implications of operating at minimum UKC repeatedly, the vessel\'s maintenance schedule (low water is hard on engines due to shallow-water effects), and the possibility of chartering the vessel short-term to another operator if waiting. Final recommendation accounts for all financial, operational, and risk factors with explicit numbers.',
